executor_description: Download the signed contents of the envelope and the audit trail certificate by specifying the path parameters - {type} & {include_certificate}

queryParams.description: string required type can hold 2 values, "split" and "merged" | "split" -- When the type is split, then the response will return a .zip extension which contains the document(s) and the audit trail in 2 separate files. | "merged" -- When the type is merged, the API will return a single PDF response including both the document(s) and the audit trail certificate
boolean required include_certificate holds values true/false or 0/1 which determines to include audit trail in the download folder.

executor_description: This API is used for embedded self signing of an original file. This API returns an URL which lets you either open the document for signing it yourself. This link can be embedded on your website / mobile apps to enable the functionality within the custom defined flow.

executor_display_name: Download certificate of a self signed document
executor_description: Download the signature certificate of the embedded self signed document created using self signing as a PDF document  An audit trail is a signature certificate from SignEasy, with details on when each signer in a signature request has signed the document and when the request was complete. The audit trail is sent to you over email by default along with the final signed document (only if the signature request was not signed via embedded signing).  Use this API to fetch the audit-trail for a completed signature request, using the signed file ID. This API works on signed documents, even if they are deleted from your account.  The API returns a PDF of the audit trail which you can store for your records.

The API is used to download the file content of a individual pending file as PDF by using the pending_file_id.  The pending_file_id is passed as a query parameter to the redirect_url passed in the Fetch RS sending URL request.

The API is used to cancel the signers of an individual pending file by using the pending_file_id.  The API also sends cancellations emails and a callback event (rs.cancelled) with data to a predefined URL endpoint configured using the callbacks API.  The pending_file_id is passed as a query parameter to the redirect url in the Fetch RS sending URL request.
This API returns a URL for a sender to request a signature from any of the recipients. The sender can also add extra fields and assign them to a signer before sending.

Retrieve information about all the pending files sent using the embedded sending API for a user, including all the pending files if they are the owner or recipient.  This API returns a response irrespective of whether the pending file is complete, incomplete, cancelled or recipient_declined.

The API is used to fetch the signing link for an individual signer of a particular signature request sent using the RS Embedded Sending URL with embedded_signing enabled.  You can use this link to get documents signed on your own website or mobile app. The pending_file_id is passed as a query parameter to the redirect_url passed in the Fetch RS sending URL request.

In case of sequential signing, the next recipient in line to sign the document is reminded. In case of parallel signing, all signers who are yet to sign the document will be reminded.  The API sends emails and a callback event (rs.remind) with data to a predefined URL endpoint configured.  In case of requests enabled using the embedded_signing option only the callback event is triggered.

executor_description: Upload a new document as an original to Signeasy to use it for signing (either yourself or others) via the envelope APIs.  The file can be gzip compressed to make the upload faster. In such cases Content-Encoding header must be passed as gzip for the server to recognise the compression. Any request without the Content-Encoding header is counted as an uncompressed file upload which may lead to a server error.

Generate an embeddable link to sign multiple documents in one go  Initiate a bulk signing request for a recipient in the signing queue and generate an embeddable link to sign up to 25 documents in bulk.  Bulk signing supports all envelope signature requests with an ordered signing flow, initiated with the is_ordered property set to true. Note that, the person to bulk sign the documents must be the next one in the signing order.
This endpoint is used to track the status of the bulk signing requests.
